2026-07-24T05:57:25.2576725Z               "distinct": false,
2026-07-24T05:57:25.2577174Z               "id": "75348bcb992f11712dec7b269e02f870abf8de21",
2026-07-24T05:57:25.2586263Z               "message": "Default SSO to the secret-less ID-token flow; keep code flow configurable\n\nThe interactive OIDC flow previously used response_type=code, which on\nEntra ID forces a client secret (or certificate) on the token-endpoint\nexchange — a credential that expires and must be rotated. ednsv only\nauthenticates users (it never calls downstream APIs on their behalf), so it\ndoes not need the token endpoint at all.\n\n- Auth:Oidc:ResponseType (default \"id_token\") and Auth:Oidc:ResponseMode\n  (default \"form_post\"): the signed, nonce-bound ID token is returned\n  directly from the authorization endpoint and validated against the IdP's\n  published (auto-rotating) signing keys — no client secret or certificate\n  to manage. Access-token-bearing response types are rejected at startup;\n  only id_token, code, and code id_token are accepted.\n- ClientSecret is now only relevant when ResponseType includes \"code\"\n  (required by Entra; public client + PKCE works on IdPs that allow it).\n- Docs: configuration.md documents the flow choice and secret semantics;\n  entra-setup.md makes the secret-less registration (tick \"ID tokens\") the\n  primary path with the code flow as a collapsible alternative.\n\nTests: default challenge now asserts response_type=id_token +\nresponse_mode=form_post + nonce; a new test pins that ResponseType=code\nstill produces the code+PKCE challenge.\n\nCo-Authored-By: Claude Fable 5 <noreply@anthropic.com>\nClaude-Session: https://claude.ai/code/session_01PRd7GEH8at5RYwqsD6AdGN",
2026-07-24T05:57:25.2591875Z               "timestamp": "2026-07-23T00:17:25Z",
2026-07-24T05:57:25.2592222Z               "tree_id": "2588d3325fbfc4cf2d5db3ad96e7cddb56214ce7",
2026-07-24T05:57:25.2592742Z               "url": "https://github.com/pkinerd/ednsv/commit/75348bcb992f11712dec7b269e02f870abf8de21"
2026-07-24T05:57:25.2593184Z             },
2026-07-24T05:57:25.2593517Z             {
2026-07-24T05:57:25.2593706Z               "author": {
2026-07-24T05:57:25.2593950Z                 "email": "noreply@anthropic.com",
2026-07-24T05:57:25.2594231Z                 "name": "Claude",
2026-07-24T05:57:25.2594468Z                 "username": "claude"
2026-07-24T05:57:25.2594701Z               },
2026-07-24T05:57:25.2594897Z               "committer": {
2026-07-24T05:57:25.2595149Z                 "email": "noreply@anthropic.com",
2026-07-24T05:57:25.2595433Z                 "name": "Claude",
2026-07-24T05:57:25.2595682Z                 "username": "claude"
2026-07-24T05:57:25.2595919Z               },
2026-07-24T05:57:25.2596116Z               "distinct": false,
2026-07-24T05:57:25.2596394Z               "id": "024e3f5023534cb5c3b3cbcf469aa9c323c13f43",
2026-07-24T05:57:25.2600962Z               "message": "docs: document why the secret-less ID-token flow is the default + its security properties\n\nThe docs stated the flow was secret-less but didn't explain why it's an\nappropriate default or lay out its security posture. Add a \"Why id_token is\nthe default, and its security properties\" subsection to configuration.md:\nthe least-privilege rationale (auth-only app holds no client credential), why\nthe general \"avoid implicit\" guidance (RFC 9700) doesn't apply here (it targets\naccess tokens in the URL fragment, which ednsv never requests), and the\nconcrete mitigations — no access tokens (enforced at startup), form_post\ndelivery, signature/audience/issuer validation against rotating keys, nonce\nreplay protection, single-use-then-discarded token, and the HTTPS requirement.\nNote when to prefer the code flow. entra-setup.md links to it.\n\nDocs only; no code changes.\n\nCo-Authored-By: Claude Fable 5 <noreply@anthropic.com>\nClaude-Session: https://claude.ai/code/session_01PRd7GEH8at5RYwqsD6AdGN",
